00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:41.290
So there's CMS.301.

00:00:41.290 --> 00:00:44.070
It's Introduction to
Game Design Methods.

00:00:44.070 --> 00:00:46.570
If you're interested
in design research,

00:00:46.570 --> 00:00:48.820
if you're interested
in design methods,

00:00:48.820 --> 00:00:51.110
and you happen to also
be interested in games,

00:00:51.110 --> 00:00:54.060
but you're likely going to
be doing things in design

00:00:54.060 --> 00:00:57.010
elsewhere-- so that might
be application design,

00:00:57.010 --> 00:01:00.519
toy design, anything physical,
anything game-like, whatever.

00:01:00.519 --> 00:01:02.310
The methods they're
going to teach in there

00:01:02.310 --> 00:01:04.143
are going to be useful
for all those things.

00:01:04.143 --> 00:01:07.540
But the class is focused on
using game design as a way

00:01:07.540 --> 00:01:11.650
to talk about design
methods-- so CMS.301.

00:01:11.650 --> 00:01:17.420
CMS.608 is a class Phillip
teaches, and I co-teach

00:01:17.420 --> 00:01:19.210
with him, on game
design-- so if you

00:01:19.210 --> 00:01:24.390
want to know more about
how games are designed.

00:01:24.390 --> 00:01:27.390
Some topics we talk about
are things like game balance,

00:01:27.390 --> 00:01:29.400
tuning.

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:31.690
The projects are all board
games and card games.

00:01:31.690 --> 00:01:34.390
So the entire class is done
with analog game design.

00:01:34.390 --> 00:01:38.180
So we can actually get more
detail into how rules work,

00:01:38.180 --> 00:01:39.989
how rules mix together.

00:01:39.989 --> 00:01:41.280
We play a bunch of board games.

00:01:41.280 --> 00:01:42.400
We analyze them.

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:43.776
And then we make board games.

00:01:43.776 --> 00:01:45.650
It's very similarly
structured to this class.

00:01:45.650 --> 00:01:46.910
It's team-based.

00:01:46.910 --> 00:01:52.450
You'll do four game design
projects in that class.

00:01:52.450 --> 00:01:56.670
There is CMS.610.

00:01:56.670 --> 00:02:01.610
That is Media Industries and
Systems, the Art, Science,

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:02.790
and Business of Games.

00:02:02.790 --> 00:02:06.130
That's taught by Chris Weaver
from Bethesda Softworks.

00:02:06.130 --> 00:02:10.669
He worked on the Elder
Scrolls series for a while.

00:02:10.669 --> 00:02:14.612
His class is focused on
the business and publisher

00:02:14.612 --> 00:02:16.320
side of the equation
of game development.

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:18.200
So if you're thinking
about doing this

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:21.164
as a professional
career, at some point

00:02:21.164 --> 00:02:23.330
you're likely going to have
to deal with publishers.

00:02:23.330 --> 00:02:25.140
Either you're going
to be working for one,

00:02:25.140 --> 00:02:27.140
you're at a studio that
will be working for one,

00:02:27.140 --> 00:02:28.830
or you will be pitching
to one yourself.

00:02:28.830 --> 00:02:31.920
So the big focus of
that class is the pitch.

00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:35.610
How do you pitch your
ideas to another group?

00:02:35.610 --> 00:02:37.580
And it's also
focused on the demo.

00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:40.430
So if anybody's heard
of the term E3 demo--

00:02:40.430 --> 00:02:42.280
basically how to make
your game look good

00:02:42.280 --> 00:02:44.480
even though it doesn't work.

00:02:44.480 --> 00:02:45.980
Hopefully the game
works at the end.

00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:48.830
But it's really focused on,
what do you need in your game

00:02:48.830 --> 00:02:50.980
in order to communicate
that game to another person

00:02:50.980 --> 00:02:55.430
in order to provide
funding for your game?

00:02:55.430 --> 00:02:57.400
So that's CMS.610.

00:02:57.400 --> 00:02:58.580
It's a really great course.

00:02:58.580 --> 00:03:00.280
He has a lot of really
good war stories

00:03:00.280 --> 00:03:02.340
from what the game
development process

00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:05.360
was like from the '80s on up.

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:12.330
