00:35:22.590 --> 00:35:24.780
and not fiction that
might be not known

00:35:24.780 --> 00:35:27.090
or might undermine the idea.

00:35:27.090 --> 00:35:30.470
One thing to keep in mind
with the fantastical-- studies

00:35:30.470 --> 00:35:32.760
have found that
some games-- when

00:35:32.760 --> 00:35:35.630
it comes to pandemics
and outbreaks,

00:35:35.630 --> 00:35:39.150
using the zombie fiction
actually can work sometimes.

00:35:39.150 --> 00:35:41.910
There is something to be said
about using a common fiction

00:35:41.910 --> 00:35:43.260
that people know.

00:35:43.260 --> 00:35:45.920
People can say, all
right, I understand

00:35:45.920 --> 00:35:48.390
how zombie pandemics work.

00:35:48.390 --> 00:35:50.556
Because I've seen all
these films about it.

00:35:50.556 --> 00:35:52.430
Whereas if you just told
me it was a disease,

00:35:52.430 --> 00:35:53.910
I might not have
seen enough films

00:35:53.910 --> 00:35:58.070
that had anything about how
disease actually spread.

00:35:58.070 --> 00:36:00.000
So really think about
what is your problem?

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:01.680
What fictions might be useful?

00:36:01.680 --> 00:36:04.025
What narratives might be
useful for the problem

00:36:04.025 --> 00:36:04.900
that you're fighting?

00:36:04.900 --> 00:36:07.910
PHILLIP TAN: Use fiction to
keep the topics relatable.

00:36:07.910 --> 00:36:11.659
And if that means drawing on
things in popular culture,

00:36:11.659 --> 00:36:12.200
that's great.

00:36:12.200 --> 00:36:13.540
That's a tool in your hand.

00:36:13.540 --> 00:36:16.780
Don't use fiction
as a way to paper

00:36:16.780 --> 00:36:19.520
over design problems,
which I've often seen.

00:36:19.520 --> 00:36:21.250
You know, if we set
this game in space,

00:36:21.250 --> 00:36:25.100
then we can sort of skip over
all reality, or something

00:36:25.100 --> 00:36:26.757
like that.

00:36:26.757 --> 00:36:28.840
When you're brainstorming,
make sure you know what

00:36:28.840 --> 00:36:29.850
you're brainstorming about.

00:36:29.850 --> 00:36:31.240
Are you brainstorming mechanics?

00:36:31.240 --> 00:36:33.500
Is it about what people
are going to be doing?

00:36:33.500 --> 00:36:36.980
Are you brainstorming what
the fiction is going to be?

00:36:36.980 --> 00:36:39.180
I would say do a separate
brainstorming session

00:36:39.180 --> 00:36:40.388
for each one of these things.

00:36:40.388 --> 00:36:42.232
Maybe just spend 10 minutes.

00:36:42.232 --> 00:36:44.190
You don't have to brainstorm
every single thing

00:36:44.190 --> 00:36:46.310
that we're showing you here.

00:36:46.310 --> 00:36:50.430
You could brainstorm what is
they aim and impact that you

00:36:50.430 --> 00:36:52.400
want to achieve in this game?

00:36:52.400 --> 00:36:53.840
How are you going to do that?

00:36:53.840 --> 00:36:56.170
Are all of you even
on the same page

00:36:56.170 --> 00:37:00.550
about what you want your
game-- the kind of change

00:37:00.550 --> 00:37:02.730
you want to see in the world?

00:37:02.730 --> 00:37:04.410
And that's going
to be your purpose.

00:37:04.410 --> 00:37:08.590
That is going to be-- do you all
understand what this thing is?

00:37:08.590 --> 00:37:10.200
A lot of it has been
defined for you.

00:37:10.200 --> 00:37:13.080
But I'm not guaranteeing
that everybody on your team

00:37:13.080 --> 00:37:14.990
necessarily shares
the same idea.

00:37:14.990 --> 00:37:18.700
So the brainstorming process
might be able to get that out.

00:37:18.700 --> 00:37:23.050
And at some point in time
within the next couple of weeks,

00:37:23.050 --> 00:37:25.681
